{{Other people|Salwa}} [[File:Les rebelles libyens préparent la transition démocratique (5739912825).jpg|thumb|Salwa El-Deghali in 2011.]] '''Salwa Fawzi El-Deghali''' ({{lang-ar|سلوى فوزي الدغٌيلًي}}) is a [[Libya]]n academic and a member of the [[National Transitional Council]] representing women and in charge of legal affairs.<ref name=list>{{cite web|title=National Transitional Council|url=http://ntclibya.com/InnerPage.aspx?SSID=7&ParentID=3&LangID=1|publisher=[[National Transitional Council]]|accessdate=25 August 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61DEzFbAb|archivedate=25 August 2011|location=[[Benghazi]]|year=2011}}</ref> El-Deghali possess a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] in [[constitutional law]]. She taught at the [[Academy of Graduate Studies]] in [[Benghazi]].<ref name=list/>
El-Deghali is one of three women on the [[National Transitional Council]], though she is the only one who has been publicly identified.<ref>{{cite news|last=Faul|first=Michelle|title=Libyan rebel says up to 2 years needed for vote|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/may/26/libyan-rebel-says-2-years-needed-vote/|accessdate=28 August 2011|newspaper=[[The Washington Times]]|date=26 May 2011|agency=[[News World Communications]]|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]}}</ref> El-Deghali represents women's interests and also is responsible for Legal Affairs; she heads the Legal Advisory Committee as part of this role.<ref name=list/> She has warned against the possibility of a pro-Gaddafi [[fifth column]] within the [[National Liberation Army (Libya)|National Liberation Army]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kaste|first=Martin|title=Rebel Council Bolstered As NATO Pounds Tripoli|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/05/24/136606043/nato-unleashes-heaviest-airstrikes-yet-on-tripoli|accessdate=28 August 2011|newspaper=[[NPR]]|date=24 May 2011|agency=National Public Radio, Inc.|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]}}</ref> Her position also gives her the responsibility of investigating the crimes of [[2011 Libyan civil war#Mercenaries|mercenaries]] employed by [[Muammar Gaddafi]] and collecting and presenting evidence of his [[war crime]]s to the [[International Criminal Court]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Elourfi|first=Asmaa|title=Rebel government prepares for move to Tripoli|url=http://www.magharebia.com/cocoon/awi/xhtml1/en_GB/features/awi/features/2011/08/25/feature-03|accessdate=28 August 2011|newspaper=[[Magharebia]]|date=25 August 2011|agency=[[United States Africa Command]]|location=[[North Africa]]}}</ref> Her primary responsibility will be to help form a functioning government, writing laws to be in effect during the transition period, and preparing for [[election]]s.<ref name=interview>{{cite news|last=Elourfi|first=Asmaa|title=Libya rebels prepare for democratic transition|url=http://www.magharebia.com/cocoon/awi/xhtml1/en_GB/features/awi/features/2011/05/19/feature-01|accessdate=28 August 2011|newspaper=[[Magharebia]]|date=19 May 2011|agency=[[United States Africa Command]]|location=[[North Africa]]}}</ref> However, she has stated that the job of writing a constitution for the country will fall to an elected assembly and not her Legal Advisory Committee.<ref name=interview/>
